Pete,

There are a couple of problems.  First of all, file nasa.cti only  
contains species data, so these definitions need to be imported into an  
&quot;ideal_gas&quot; entry in another .cti file.  You can write a simple one  
like this:

ideal_gas(name = &quot;gas&quot;,
          elements = &quot;O H C N Ar Al E&quot;,
          species = &quot;nasa:all &quot;,
           options = [&#39;skip_undeclared_elements&#39;],
           initial_state = state(temperature = 300.0, pressure = OneAtm)
           )

Set the element list to whatever elements you are interested in - the  
rest of the species will be skipped. But note that this will pick up  
the liquid and solid species in nasa.cti too.  To get rid of these,  
edit nasa.cti first.

But there are 2 more minor problems.  File nasa.cti has a formatting  
error - there is a comma missing on the line before &quot;note&quot; in each  
entry. So open it in a text editor and globally replace &quot;note&quot; by  
either &quot;, note&quot; or by &quot;# note&quot;.

The next problem is that the species import process expects to find an  
xml file, not a cti file (this will be fixed someday).  So run program  
&#39;cti2ctml&#39; on nasa.cti to generate nasa.xml.  Or just get nasa.xml  
here:

http://rayleigh.cds.caltech.edu/~goodwin/nasa.xml

In the modified &#39;demo.cpp&#39; program, use the .cti file with the  
ideal_gas entry listed above, and it should work.

Dave



